sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: IR-3-GFP
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This device is made up of three parts: a LuxI producer, a Lux R producer and a GFP reporter. It is used to test the efficiency of promoter lux pR(BBa_R0062) and its mutants lux pR-3 (BBa_K658006), lux pR-5 (BBa_K658007), lux pR-3/5 (BBa_K658008).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Xin Wu
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Similar to the definition of RBS strength, the strength of promoters lux pR and its three mutants could be tested using this device.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K658013
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: 3OC6HSL Sender and Receiver Device with lux pR-3 Driven by PLlac 0-1
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Quorum sensing is used by a number of gram-negative bacterial genera to regulate expression of specific sets of genes in a cell density-dependent fashion. We constructed the part which expresses LuxI and LuxR upon induction by isopropyl-b-D-thiogalactopyranoside (IPTG). There are two regulatory genes involved in quorum sensing, the I and R genes. The I gene directs the synthesis of an acyl-homoserine lactone (AHL) signal molecule termed the autoinducer. The R gene codes for a transcription factor that is responsive to the N-acyl HSL signal. Cells are permeable to this signal, and thus high cell densities are required to achieve a critical concentration of the autoinducer required to bind the luxR product, which will be combined with lux pR and then the expression downstream genes could be started. Site-directed mutagenesis has been used to modify the promoter lux pR in this signalling device. We have generated three point mutants by site-directed mutagenesis, designated lux pR-3 (BBa_K658006), lux pR-5(BBa_K658007) and lux pR-3/5(BBa_K658008). This signalling device is usually used to connected with some protein coding sequence,The promoter lux pR-3 (BBa_K658006) at the end of this sequence regulates the expression of downstream genes.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Yijuan Huang
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This signalling device is based on the quorum sensing system in V. Fischri. Different from an autoinduction system, this signalling circuit starts only at the presence of inducer IPTG which does not exist in the natural QS system.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_F1610
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This device accepts PoPS as input and produces the LuxI enzyme. This enzyme produces 3OC<sub>6</sub>HSL.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Caitlin Conboy and Jennifer Braff

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: GFP.Term
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part results from the ligation of E0040 with B0015 in the manner described on this website.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Kristen DeCelle

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: lux pR-3
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: position 3 mutated promoter lux pR-3 (luxR & HSL regulated)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The position 3 mutated promoter lux pR-3 is a product of site-directed mutagenesis of promoter lux pR (BBa_R0062). The promoter lux pR is based on the Vibrio fischeri quorum sensing gene promoters. The position 3 mutated promoter lux pR-3 gives a higher expression of downstream genes in an autoinduction system. In another word, the lux pR-3 has a higher efficiency than the lux pR. Similar to promoter lux pR, the expression is up-regulated by the action of LuxR protein combined with the signal molecule HSL.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Yidan Hu
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The position 3 mutated promoter lux pR-3 is based on promoter lux pR (BBa_R0062).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: In the promoter lux pR's sequence, the C residue of position 3 was changed to a T using PCR method.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0010
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcriptional terminator consisting of a 64 bp stem-loop.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Randy Rettberg

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: luxr
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
In complex with HSL, LuxR binds to the Lux promoter, activating transcription from Pr BBa_R0062, and repressing transcription from Pl BBa_R0063.

The lux cassette of V. fischeri contains a left and a right promoter. The right promoter gives weak constitutive expression of downstream genes.This expression is up-regulated by the action of the Lux activator, LuxR complexed to HSL. Two molecules of LuxR protein form a complex with two molecules the signalling compound homoserine lactone (HSL). This complex binds to a palindromic site on the promoter, increasing the rate of transcription.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: 2 silent point mutants were introduced in the coding sequence to remove internal XbaI and PstI sites. Mutation sites were chosen to replace codons commonly used in E. coli with codons used at a similar frequency.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: RBS based on Elowitz repressilator.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: lacI+pL
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
Inverting regulatory region controlled by LacI (BBa_C0010, BBa_C0011, etc.)

The PLlac 0-1 promoter is a hybrid regulatory region consisting of the promoter P(L) of phage lambda with the cI binding sites replaced with lacO1. The hybrid design allows for strong promotion that can nevertheless be tightly repressed by LacI, the Lac inhibitor (i.e. repressor) (BBa_C0010) ([LUTZ97]). The activity of the promoter can be regulated over a >600-fold range by IPTG in E.Coli DH5-alpha-Z1 (same paper reference).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Neelaksh Varshney, Grace Kenney, Daniel Shen, Samantha Sutton
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
hybrid promoter design to create strong promoter that is, at the same time, highly repressible. note that the upstream operator installed in this hybrid is slightly different than the one in the original source (Lutz and Bujard, 1997). the most upstream operator region is slightly truncated in the represillator version, so that both operators in the hybrid are the same sequence. see references for details. also, the sequence has been truncated after the transcriptional start site.

LacI binds to this regulator. This part is incompatible with species containing active LacI coding regions. Lactose and IPTG disable the operation of LacI and increase transcription. This part is incompatible with environments containing lactose or lactose analogs.
